# Fluff Date: 2026-03-05 17:18:25
<overview>
<p>The Durandel-British "Blue Nova" Convertible is a small wheeled civilian vehicle introduced in 3067 as an affordable entry point into the high-performance sports car market. Manufactured by Durandel-British, the design was conceived to bring the excitement of motorsport culture to average consumers who had been priced out of the premium vehicle segment. Available in both hardtop coupe and convertible configurations, the Blue Nova quickly became one of the manufacturer's best-selling models and earned the informal title of "the everyman's sportster" from automotive reviewers. Its combination of sporty styling and accessible pricing found a receptive audience among driving enthusiasts across the Inner Sphere.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Blue Nova is powered by a re-engineered 2750-model Outworlds Motors internal combustion engine, a utility vehicle powerplant adapted for the consumer sports car market. The 765-kilogram engine drives the 1,500-kilogram vehicle to a cruise speed of roughly 80 kilometers per hour with a flank speed of 120 kilometers per hour, making it considerably slower than purpose-built racing vehicles. Durandel-British partially compensates for the engine's modest output through a carefully engineered custom exhaust system that creates a convincing aural impression of greater power, though the vehicle is widely acknowledged to be underpowered in practice.</p><p>The convertible variant features a convertible chassis modification with seating for one driver and one passenger. BAR 2 rated armor provides minimal protection suited to the vehicle's purely civilian role. Fuel range of 379 kilometers on petrochemical fuel is adequate for daily commuting and recreational driving. Optional equipment packages include leather interior upholstery, a trivid entertainment system, and nitrous injectors. Even fully loaded with every available option, the convertible still costs slightly less than a base-model Scion-Nissaki Hyperion, preserving the Blue Nova's core value proposition. The vehicle offers 198 kilograms of standard cargo capacity through a single rear door.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Blue Nova serves as a civilian sports car and personal transport vehicle. Popular among middle-class enthusiasts and casual drivers across the Inner Sphere, the vehicle is commonly found in urban centers and suburban communities wherever a market for affordable performance vehicles exists. The convertible model proved particularly sought after, with demand initially outstripping available supply following the vehicle's debut.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Durandel-British developed the Blue Nova in response to growing consumer interest in high-performance vehicles during the late 3060s. Prior to its introduction, the sports car market was dominated by expensive manufacturers such as Avanti, Hughes-McCandless, and Scion-Nissaki, whose products remained well beyond the reach of ordinary citizens. The Blue Nova's 3067 debut changed this dynamic by offering a vehicle that delivered the appearance and appeal of a premium sports car at a significantly lower price point, costing nearly twenty percent less than the popular Starfire.</p><p>The key to the design's affordability was the manufacturer's decision to adapt an older utility vehicle powerplant rather than commissioning a new purpose-built engine. This cost-saving approach, paired with targeted compromises in outright performance, allowed Durandel-British to reach a price bracket that opened the market to a much broader customer base. The trade-off in raw speed was readily accepted by buyers who valued style and accessibility over track capability.</p><p>Consumer reception was immediate and enthusiastic. The Thorin Consumer's Review praised the vehicle as an accessible way to participate in high-performance vehicle culture. The distinctive shimmer paint option, which blends two opposite colors using polymer technology to create shifting hues depending on viewing angle, became particularly popular and helped establish the Blue Nova's visual identity. Consumers interested in the full experience could opt for the convertible model with all available options, though the base hardtop coupe proved equally popular for its clean styling.</p>
</history>

